'''Tyler Lee Clippard''' (born February 14, 1985) is an American [[professional baseball]] [[pitcher]]. He has pitched for the [[Washington Nationals]] in [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) since 2008. In 2007, he pitched for the [[New York Yankees]]. Clippard bats and throws [[handedness|right-handed]].

After playing baseball at [[J. W. Mitchell High School]] in [[New Port Richey, Florida]], the Yankees drafted Clippard in the ninth round of the [[2003 MLB Draft]]. He debuted with the Yankees as a [[starting pitcher]] in 2007. The Yankees traded him to the Nationals before the 2008 season, and the Nationals converted him into a [[relief pitcher]] in 2009. He was named to the [[MLB All-Star Game]] in 2011, and won the [[MLB Delivery Man of the Month Award]] in June 2012.

==Amateur career==
Clippard was born in [[Lexington, Kentucky]]. His family moved to [[Florida]] when he was a toddler.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LH&s_site=kentucky&p_multi=LH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=1194FB538200C588&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader|date=May 22, 2007|page=B4|title=Clippard Gives Yanks Solid Debut, Lexington Native Delivers Win in First Game in Majors|accessdate=July 5, 2012}} {{subscription required|date=July 2012}}</ref>  Clippard played baseball in [[Little League]]; in eleven years, he won seven district titles, but was never able to reach the [[Little League World Series]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sptimes.com/News/082301/NorthPinellas/Chemistry_leads_team_.shtml |title=Chemistry leads team to triumph: The Palm Harbor baseball team of 15- and 16-year-olds tossed aside their egos and frustrations, and won a world championship title|first=John|last=Schwarb|newspaper=[[St. Petersburg Times]] |date=August 23, 2001 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> He learned to pitch when he was eight years old.<ref name=tampabay/> In 2001, he was a member of the Palm Harbor team that won the [[Senior League World Series]].<ref name=tampabay/>

Clippard began his high school career at [[Palm Harbor University High School]] in [[Palm Harbor, Florida]]. After failing to make the varsity baseball team in his first two seasons, he transferred to [[J. W. Mitchell High School]] in [[New Port Richey, Florida]],<ref name=tampabay>{{cite news|url=http://www.tampabay.com/sports/baseball/rays/former-tampa-bay-area-player-tyler-clippard-writes-storybook-ending/1180356 |title=Former Tampa Bay area player Tyler Clippard writes storybook ending with major-league All-Star selection, win|newspaper=Tampa Bay Times|first=John |last=Romano |date=July 11, 2011 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sptimes.com/News/100901/Sports/Palm_Harbor_U_builds_.shtml |title=Sports: Palm Harbor U. builds powerhouse |newspaper=St. Petersburg Times |first=Rodney|last=Page|date=October 9, 2001 |accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref> where he played for the schoo's baseball team. As a junior, in 2002, he [[win (baseball)|won]] six games and had the second lowest [[earned run average]] (ERA) in the nation, at 1.18.<ref name=pasco/> He was named to the All-Conference first team.<ref name=milb>{{cite news|first=Alex|last=Gyr|work=[[MLB.com]] |url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20060802&content_id=113129&vkey=news_milb&fext=.jsp |title=Clippard making up for lost time: Yankees prospect started pro career close to home in Tampa |publisher=Milb.com |date=August 2, 2006 |accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref>

In 2003, his senior season, Clippard had a 1<U+2013>1 record with an 0.81 ERA and 31 strikeouts in {{frac|17|1|3}} [[innings pitched]]. However, he was dismissed from the school's baseball team after being charged with [[driving under the influence]] of alcohol.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/tampabay/access/311654421.html?dids=311654421:311654421&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Mar+20%252C+2003&author=GREG+AUMAN&pub=St.+Petersburg+Times&desc=Mitchell+irked+to+learn+of+suspended+pitcher's+DUI+arrest&pqatl=google |title=Mitchell irked to learn of suspended pitcher's DUI arrest |newspaper=St. Petersburg Times |first=Greg|last=Auman|date=March 20, 2003 |accessdate=July 4, 2012}} {{subscription required|date=July 2012}}</ref> Clippard transferred to [[Dunedin High School]] in [[Dunedin, Florida]], which had a nationally ranked baseball team. Clippard attempted to play for their team, but the move was blocked by the [[Florida High School Athletic Association]], as players are not allowed to transfer during the course of a season, nor are they allowed to transfer to avoid sanctions given for disciplinary reasons.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sptimes.com/2003/03/28/Pasco/Ex_Mustang_transfers_.shtml |title=Pasco: Ex-Mustang transfers but will be ineligible |newspaper=St. Petersburg Times |first=Greg|last=Auman |date=March 28, 2003 |accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref> After taking classes at Dunedin for a month, Clippard transferred back to Mitchell in order to graduate from high school with his friends.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sptimes.com/2005/06/03/Sports/Ex_Mustang_named_to_F.shtml |title=Sports: Ex-Mustang named to FSL all-star team |newspaper=St. Petersburg Times |first=Bob|last=Putnam |date=June 3, 2005|accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref>

Clippard competed for the Central Florida Renegades in Connie Mack Baseball, an amateur 18-and-under competition organized by the [[American Amateur Baseball Congress]]. He earned pitcher of the week honors in the Florida State Elite Baseball League in June 2003.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2003-06-14/news/0306140038_1_teams-competing-state-tournament-league-play |first=Joe|last=Williams|title=Lakers' 10-under Team Enters Tourney|newspaper=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |date=June 14, 2003 |accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref>

Clippard also played [[golf]] at Mitchell. As a sophomore, in 2001, Clippard was named one of the ten best golfers in [[Pasco County]].<ref name=pasco/> He registered the best individual score in the Sunshine Athletic Conference tournament that year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sptimes.com/News/101701/Sports/_Dogs_defend_another_.shtml |title=Sports: 'Dogs defend another title |first=Jamal|last=Thalji|newspaper=St. Petersburg Times |date=October 17, 2001 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> He was named to the All-Conference first team as a junior<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sptimes.com/News/112301/news_pf/Pasco/High_school_sports_ho.shtml|first=Jamal|last=Thalji |title=Pasco: High school sports honors |newspaper=St. Petersburg Times|date=November 23, 2001 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> and to the All-County as a senior,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/tampabay/access/270042771.html?dids=270042771:270042771&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Dec+19%252C+2002&author=GREG+AUMAN&pub=St.+Petersburg+Times&desc=BOYS+TEAM+Series%253A+BOYS+TEAM%253B+ALL-COUNTY+GOLF+TEAMS&pqatl=google |title=Boys Team Series: Boys Team; All-County Golf Teams |newspaper=St. Petersburg Times |first=Greg|last=Auman|date=December 19, 2002 |accessdate=July 4, 2012}} {{subscription required|date=July 2012}}</ref> and helped lead Mitchell to victory in the Sunshine Athletic Conference tournament during his senior year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sptimes.com/2002/10/23/Sports/Mitchell_wins_wild_to.shtml |title=Sports: Mitchell wins wild tournament |newspaper=St. Petersburg Times |date=October 23, 2002 |accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref>

==Professional career==
===Draft===
Without the benefit of a full senior season to show himself off to [[scout (sports)|scouts]], Clippard proactively sent scouts a schedule of when he was throwing and attended as many showcases as he could.<ref name=milb/> He trained with Roy Silver, a retired professional baseball player, who worked with Clippard on his mechanics and his maturity.<ref name=washingtontimes/> Clippard's father, Bob, teamed up with [[Tom Kotchman]], father of Florida high school player [[Casey Kotchman]], to form showcases with past teammates of Clippard.<ref name=tampabay/>

Clippard was drafted in the ninth round of the [[2003 Major League Baseball Draft]], with the 274th overall selection, by the [[New York Yankees]]. Though he had signed a [[National Letter of Intent]] in the fall of 2002 to attend the [[University of South Florida]] on a baseball scholarship, allowing him to play [[college baseball]] for the [[South Florida Bulls]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/tampabay/access/242573721.html?dids=242573721:242573721&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Nov+21%252C+2002&author=GREG+AUMAN&pub=St.+Petersburg+Times&desc=Mitchell's+catcher+signs+with+Tampa+Series%253A+BASEBALL&pqatl=google |title=Mitchell's catcher signs with Tampa Series |newspaper=St. Petersburg Times|first=Greg|last=Auman |date=November 21, 2002 |accessdate=July 4, 2012}} {{subscription required|date=July 2012}}</ref> he chose to turn professional due to his draft position and the opportunity to play for the Yankees.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/tampabay/access/343854621.html?dids=343854621:343854621&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jun+04%252C+2003&author=GREG+AUMAN&pub=St.+Petersburg+Times&desc=Clippard+a+ninth-round+pick+Series%253A+BASEBALL&pqatl=google |title=Clippard a ninth-round pick Series%3A BASEBALL|newspaper=St. Petersburg Times|first=Greg|last=Auman |date=June 4, 2003 |accessdate=July 4, 2012}} {{subscription required|date=July 2012}}</ref>

===New York Yankees===
Clippard made his professional debut that year in the [[Rookie-level]] [[Gulf Coast League]] (GCL) with the [[GCL Yankees]], pitching to a 3<U+2013>3 [[win-loss record (pitching)|win-loss record]] with a 2.89 ERA. In {{frac|43|2|3}} innings, he allowed 33 hits and five walks while striking out 56. Moving up to the [[Battle Creek Yankees]] of the [[Class A (baseball)|Class A]] [[Midwest League]] for the 2004 season,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/battlecreekenquirer/access/1806952401.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Apr+05%2C+2004&author=Howie+Magner&pub=Battle+Creek+Enquirer&desc=Local+Yankees+announce+'04+roster&pqatl=google |title=Local Yankees announce '04 roster |newspaper=Battle Creek Enquirer|first=Howie|last=Magner |date=April 5, 2004|accessdate=July 5, 2012}} {{subscription required|date=July 2012}}</ref> Clippard had a 10<U+2013>10 record with a 3.44 ERA and a [[strikeout-to-walk ratio]] of 4.53:1 in 25 starts.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/battlecreekenquirer/access/2418386821.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Aug+6%2C+2011&author=Alex%20McCarthy&pub=Battle+Creek+Enquirer&desc=Yanks+come+to+town&pqatl=google |title=Yanks come to town |newspaper=Battle Creek Enquirer|first=Alex|last=McCarthy |date=August 6, 2011|accessdate=July 5, 2012}} {{subscription required|date=July 2012}}</ref>

Clippard was 10<U+2013>9 with a 3.18 ERA for the [[Tampa Yankees]] of the [[Class A-Advanced]] [[Florida State League]] (FSL) in 2005. He was named to the West team in the FSL All-Star Game.<ref name=fsl>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=3-hRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=c3IDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6369,4311378&dq=tyler-clippard+mitchell&hl=en|title=Clippard gets back on pace|first=Thomas|last=Simonetti|newspaper=St. Petersburg Times|date=August 9, 2005|page=4|accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref>  However, he did not appear in the game, as the [[Charleston RiverDogs]] of the Class A [[South Atlantic League]] needed another pitcher that day.<ref name=fsl/> Clippard was named FSL pitcher of the week for the week of July 10 through 17.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sptimes.com/2005/07/22/Sports/FSL__Yankees_finally_.shtml |title=Sports: FSL: Yankees finally hit stride |newspaper=St. Petersburg Times |date=July 22, 2005 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> For the season, opponents [[batting average|batted]] .219 against him and he struck out 169 batter in {{frac|147|1|3}} innings, while walking 34. He led Yankees farmhands in strikeouts and finished fifth in the affiliated minor leagues, behind [[Francisco Liriano]], [[Joel Zumaya]], [[Rich Hill (pitcher)|Rich Hill]] and [[Chuck James]].<ref name=milb/> He also led the FSL in strikeouts and was seventh in ERA. However, he did not make the FSL post-season All-Star team<ref>{{cite news|first=Jason |last=Ratliff |work=MLB.com |url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20050830&content_id=24100&vkey=news_milb&fext=.jsp |title=FSL All-Stars: Tigers, Dodgers galore; First-half champs claim nine of 18 spots on postseason roster |publisher=Milb.com |date=August 30, 2005 |accessdate=July 8, 2012}}</ref> and ''[[Baseball America]]'' did not rank him as one of the league's top prospects.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/today/minors/05league20s/fsl.html |title=2005 Top 20 Prospects: Florida State League |publisher=Baseball America |date=September 28, 2005 |accessdate=July 8, 2012}}</ref>

''Baseball America'' ranked Clippard as the Yankees' tenth best prospect heading into the 2006 season.<ref name=osc2006>{{cite web|url=http://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/?id=3366354 |title=Clippard named Eastern League Pitcher of the Week&nbsp;<U+2013> OurSports Central&nbsp;<U+2013> Independent and Minor League Sports News |publisher=OurSports Central |date= |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> Promoted to the [[Trenton Thunder]] of the [[Class AA]] [[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]] in 2006, Clippard again led Yankee farmhands in strikeouts (175). He allowed just a .200 batting average and had three times as many strikeouts as walks. Clippard was 12<U+2013>10 with a 3.35 ERA for the [[Trenton Thunder]]. He threw the first [[no-hitter]] in franchise history on August 17, shutting down the [[Harrisburg Senators]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=PI&s_site=philly&p_multi=PI&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=113AF5A4D7517B80&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|newspaper=[[Philadelphia Inquirer]]|title=Trenton's Clippard tosses no-hitter|page=C03|date=August 18, 2006|accessdate=July 5, 2012}} {{subscription required|date=July 2012}}</ref> He was named the Eastern League's pitcher of the week for his accomplishment.<ref name=osc2006/> Earlier in the season, Clippard flirted with a [[perfect game]], retiring the first 21 batters in a game against the [[Binghamton Mets]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/?id=3318496 |title=B-Mets Break Up Perfecto, But Lose In The Ninth|publisher=OurSports Central |date=May 29, 2006 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> Clippard also won nine straight games at one point, breaking the club record of eight shared by [[Tomo Ohka]] and [[Carl Pavano]]. He teamed with [[Phil Hughes]] to form one of the best pitching duos in minor league baseball.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20060903&content_id=127512&vkey=news_milb&fext=.jsp|title=Eastern League playoff preview: Portland vs. Trenton/Altoona vs. Akron|first=Jonathan|last=Mayo|work=MLB.com|publisher=Minor League Baseball|date=September 5, 2006|accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref> Clippard again was fifth in the affiliated minors in strikeouts, trailing [[Yovani Gallardo]], [[Francisco Cruceta]], [[Matt Maloney (baseball)|Matt Maloney]] and [[Franklin Morales]]. He led the Eastern League in strikeouts and was seventh in ERA. ''Baseball America'' ranked him as the tenth-best prospect in the Eastern League.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/today/prospects/rankings/league-top-20-prospects/2006/262558.html|title=Eastern League Top 20 Prospects List: Hughes stands out in deep EL pitching crop|first=Alan|last=Matthews|publisher=Baseball America|date=October 5, 2006|accessdate=July 10, 2012}}</ref>

Clippard began 2007 with the [[Scranton/Wilkes-Barre Yankees]] of the Class AAA International League. He was 3<U+2013>2 with a 2.72 ERA in his first eight starts, striking out 41 in 39 2/3 innings but allowing 40 hits and 17 walks. Though the Yankees experienced injuries in the starting rotation, they called on [[Matt DeSalvo]] and [[Chase Wright]] before Clippard.<ref name=sny/> When [[Darrell Rasner]] broke his finger in May, Clippard was called up to New York. He became the seventh rookie to start a game for the [[2007 New York Yankees]], following Hughes, DeSalvo, Rasner, Wright, [[Kei Igawa]] and [[Jeff Karstens]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Matuszewski |first=Erik |url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=a024fXvdHKak&refer=home |title=Yankees Face First Sweep Against Mets Since July 2004  |publisher=Bloomberg |date=May 20, 2007 |accessdate=July 6, 2012}}</ref>

Making his MLB debut on May 20, 2007, in an [[interleague]] game against the [[New York Mets]], Clippard recorded his first MLB win.<ref name=first/> He pitched six innings, giving up one [[Run (baseball)|run]] off the bat of [[David Wright (baseball)|David Wright]] and three hits. He struck out his first major league batter, [[Jos<U+00E9> Reyes (shortstop)|Jos<U+00E9> Reyes]], on three pitches. He recorded his first career hit in his second [[at-bat]] off Mets pitcher [[Scott Schoeneweis]], a [[Double (baseball)|double]] to right center in the sixth inning.<ref name=first>{{cite news| last=Hoch| first=Bryan| title=Clippard neutralizes Mets in debut| url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/gameday_recap.jsp?ymd=20070520&content_id=1976925&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=nyy| work=MLB.com|publisher=[[Major League Baseball Advanced Media]] |date=May 21, 2007| accessdate=May 21, 2007}}</ref> Clippard was optioned back to the minor leagues in June.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=pPlRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gXQDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6495,3314059&dq=tyler-clippard+mitchell&hl=en|title=Baseball Notebook: Orioles end 7-year odyssey|first=John C.|last=Cotey|newspaper=St. Petersburg Times|page=6|date=June 19, 2007|accessdate=July 10, 2012}}</ref> He struggled in his return to the minor leagues for Scranton/Wilkes-Barre,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=WB&s_site=timesleader&p_multi=WB&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=11AC158DA0F466C0&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|newspaper=Times Leader|date=July 22, 2007|page=1C|title=Charlotte Snaps SWB Streak At 5|accessdate=July 8, 2012}} {{subscription required|date=July 2012}}</ref> and was demoted to Trenton in July.<ref>{{cite news|first=Bryan|last=Hoch|work=MLB.com |url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070724&content_id=279494&vkey=news_l117&fext=.jsp&sid=l117 |title=Chamberlain, Kennedy promoted: Yankees move top pitching prospects to Scranton/Wilkes-Barre |publisher=Milb.com |date=July 24, 2007 |accessdate=July 6, 2012}}</ref> Though he was a member of the Trenton team as they won the Eastern League championship, Clippard struggled in the playoffs.<ref name=sny>{{cite web|url=http://www.sny.tv/news/article.jsp?ymd=20071017&content_id=1440168&oid=36977&vkey=44&print=true&print=true |title=News: Yankees' top prospects |work=SNY.tv |publisher=[[SportsNet New York]]|first=Nate |last=Freiberg|date=November 15, 2007 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> The Yankees recalled him in September.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/baltsun/access/1337595641.html?dids=1337595641:1337595641&FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:FT&type=current&date=Sep+18%2C+2007&author=Anonymous&pub=The+Sun&desc=TRANSACTIONS&pqatl=google |title=Transactions |page=D.3|newspaper=[[The Baltimore Sun|The Sun]]|date=September 18, 2007 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}} {{subscription required|date=July 2012}}</ref> Overall with, he had a 3<U+2013>1 record and a 6.33 ERA with the Yankees.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=mlb&id=3143069 |title=Yankees trade RHP Tyler Clippard to Nationals for reliever Jonathan Albaladejo |work=ESPN.com|publisher=ESPN |date=December 5, 2007 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref>

===Washington Nationals===
Clippard was traded on December 4, 2007, to the [[Washington Nationals]] for [[relief pitcher]] [[Jonathan Albaladejo]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Hoch|first=Bryan|title=Clippard dealt to Nats for Albaladejo|publisher=[[MLB.com]]|date=December 4, 2007|url =http://newyork.yankees.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20071204&content_id=2317008&vkey=news_nyy&fext=.jsp&c_id=nyy|accessdate =2007-12-03 }}</ref> The Nationals viewed him as a contender for a spot in the starting rotation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=jI80AAAAIBAJ&sjid=CKIFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4262,8933800&dq=tyler-clippard&hl=en|title=Remade Nationals mix of young, old|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|page=D5|date=December 12, 2007|accessdate=July 10, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fcnp.com/arts/2563-picking-splinters-a-few-nats-notes.html |title=Picking Splinters: A Few Nats Notes &#124; Falls Church News-Press Online |first=Mike|last=Hume|newspaper=[[Falls Church News-Press]] |date=February 20, 2008 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> However, he began the season with the [[Columbus Clippers]], Washington's Class AAA affiliate.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=WT&p_theme=wt&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=11F5AC831B6EA4E0&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=Balester, Clippard headed to minors|date=March 11, 2008|newspaper=The Washington Times|accessdate=July 10, 2012}} {{subscription required|date=July 2012}}</ref> He pitched his first game for the Nationals on June 9, {{mlby|2008}}, after [[Odalis P<U+00E9>rez]] was placed on the 15-day [[disabled list]]. He was optioned to the minor leagues after this start,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080609&content_id=2878739&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb&partnered=rss_mlb |title=Belliard activated from DL |work=MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball Advanced Media |date=June 9, 2008 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> but was given a second start a few days later, as P<U+00E9>rez was not yet ready to return.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080612&content_id=2898799&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=Clippard expected to pitch Saturday |work=MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball Advanced Media |date=June 12, 2008 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> The Nationals then optioned Clippard to Columbus after his second start, in which Clippard pitched to a 1<U+2013>1 record and 4.35 ERA.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080616&content_id=2943211&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=Clippard optioned to Triple-A Columbus|work=MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball Advanced Media |date=June 16, 2008 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> He was recalled later in June as [[Shawn Hill]] was placed on the disabled list.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2008/jun/26/clippard-likely-to-replace-hill-in-the-rotation/ |title=Clippard likely to start |newspaper=The Washington Times |date=June 26, 2008 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> He spent most of the season with Columbus, going 6<U+2013>13 with a 4.66 ERA. He tied [[Yorman Bazardo]] and [[Charlie Haeger]] for the most losses in the [[International League]] that season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com:8080/minors/leader.cgi?type=pitch&id=6d94d0d7 |title=2008 International League Pitching Leaders |work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]] |publisher=Sports Reference LLC |date= |accessdate=July 8, 2012}}</ref>

[[File:Tyler Clippard 2009.jpg|left|upright|thumb|Clippard during the 2009 season]]
During [[spring training]] in 2009, the Nationals optioned Clippard to the [[Syracuse Chiefs]], Washington's new Class AAA affiliate.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/nl/2009-03-16-3396424881_x.htm |title=Nationals send Clippard, Maxwell to Triple A |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=March 16, 2009 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> Despite starting six games with the [[New York Yankees|Yankees]] in 2007 and two for the Nationals in 2008, he was converted to a relief pitcher for the 2009 campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090504&content_id=4554684&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb&partnerId=rss_mlb |title=Clippard adjusting well to bullpen move |work=MLB.com |publisher=Major League Baseball Advanced Media |date=May 4, 2012 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> Nationals' [[coach (baseball)|pitching coach]] [[Steve McCatty]] told Clippard that his future was pitching in relief, because his [[pitch count]] tended to get too high in starts, and opposing batters hit Clippard well by the third time the lineup turned over in a game.<ref name=washingtontimes/> Clippard at first resisted the transition to the bullpen, but conversations with his father and agent, [[Casey Close]], reassured him to continue pursuing his dream.<ref>{{cite news|first=Ben|last=Goessling|url=http://www.masnsports.com/the_goessling_game/2011/07/with-all-star-selection-clippards-faith-pays-off.html |title=The Goessling Game: With All-Star selection, Clippard's faith pays off |publisher=[[MASN]]|work=Masnsports.com |date=July 11, 2011 |accessdate=July 6, 2012}}</ref> Clippard appeared in 20 games for Syracuse in 2009, posting a 4<U+2013>1 record, 0.92 ERA, and 42 [[strikeouts]] in 39 [[innings]].<ref name=espn/> Clippard pitched in 14 consecutive scoreless appearances before being promoted to the Nationals on June 21, 2009, replacing [[Kip Wells]] in the Nationals' bullpen.<ref name=espn>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=4284898 |title=Washington Nationals designate Kip Wells, call up Tyler Clippard for 'pen|publisher=ESPN |work=ESPN.com |date=June 24, 2009 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> Used sparingly in the first weeks after his promotion,<ref>{{cite news|last=Harlan |first=Chico|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/nationalsjournal/2009/07/burnett_and_the_rest_of_the_bu.html |work=Nationals Journal|title=Burnett And The Rest Of The Bullpen |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=July 11, 2009 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> he posted a 2.69 ERA through {{frac|60|1|3}} [[innings]], with 67 [[strikeouts]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2009/oct/06/nats-want-a-lot-from-a-little/|title=Nats want a lot from a little|first=Mark|last=Zuckerman|newspaper=The Washington Times|date=October 6, 2009|accessdate=July 10, 2012}}</ref>

Since 2010, Clippard has pitched exclusively out of the bullpen; primarily in the eighth inning.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kilgore |first=Adam |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/nationalsjournal/2010/07/drew_storen_tyler_clippard_wil.html |work=Nationals Journal|title=Drew Storen, Tyler Clippard will be sharing roles |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=July 4, 2010 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> That season, Clippard and [[Drew Storen]] served as [[setup pitcher]]s to [[Matt Capps]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Tristan H. |last=Cockcroft|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/fantasy/baseball/flb/story?page=re100610 |title=Tyler Clippard and Drew Storen are waiting in the wings should Matt Capps fail to hold his closer's gig&nbsp;<U+2013> Fantasy Baseball&nbsp;<U+2013> ESPN |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=June 16, 2010 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> After pitching effectively in the first half of the season, Clippard and Capps earned the nickname "Clip and Save".<ref>{{cite web|last=Kilgore |first=Adam |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/nationalsjournal/2010/06/the_return_of_clip_save.html |title=Nationals Journal&nbsp;<U+2013> The return of Clip & Save |publisher=Voices.washingtonpost.com |date=June 22, 2010 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> Clippard finished eighth in the [[National League]] in appearances, with 78.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/NL/2010-pitching-leaders.shtml |title=2010 National League Pitching Leaders |work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC |date= |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> He won eleven games on the season,<ref name=allstarwin>{{cite news|first=Jim |last=Caple |url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/allstar11/story/_/id/6764567/clippard-gets-all-star-win-out |title=Clippard gets All-Star win without an out|publisher=ESPN|work=ESPN.com |date=July 12, 2011 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> which led the team.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kilgore |first=Adam |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/nationalsjournal/2010/09/tyler_clippard_and_the_nationa.html |work=Nationals Journal|title=Tyler Clippard, and the Nationals bullpen, win again |newspaper=The Washington Post|date=September 23, 2010 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref>

In the first half of the 2011 season, Clippard had a 1<U+2013>0 record and 1.73 ERA.<ref name=allstarwin/> He struck out 63 batters and allowed only 26 hits in {{frac|51|1|3}} innings pitched, and allowed only six of 32 [[inherited runner]]s to score.<ref name=washingtontimes/><ref name=allstarwin/> For his achievements, Clippard was selected to appear in the [[2011 MLB All-Star Game]].<ref name=washingtontimes/> He earned the victory for the National League as the game's winning pitcher, despite not retiring a batter.<ref name=allstarwin/><ref>{{cite news|last=Kepner |first=Tyler |url=http://bats.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/07/16/from-yankees-rotation-to-nationals-bullpen-and-thriving/ |title=From Yankees' Rotation to Nationals' Bullpen, and Thriving|newspaper=The New York Times |date=July 16, 2011 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> [[Adrian Beltre]], the only batter Clippard faced, singled, but [[Hunter Pence]] threw out [[Jose Bautista]] at [[home plate]], and the NL took the lead in the next inning.<ref name=allstarwin/> Clippard finished the season with a 3<U+2013>0 record, a 1.83 ERA, and 104 strikeouts in {{frac|88|1|3}} innings pitched across 72 appearances.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=385371 |title=Zimmermann, Gorzelanny agree to deals with Nationals |publisher=Tsn.ca |date= |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> He led the National League in [[win probability added]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/NL/2011-pitching-leaders.shtml|title=2011 National League Pitching Leaders|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=June 11, 2012}}</ref>

Before the 2012 season, Clippard and the Nationals agreed to a one-year contract worth $1.65 million, avoiding [[salary arbitration]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsok.com/zimmermann-gorzelanny-clippard-agree-with-nats/article/feed/336702?custom_click=pod_headline_mlb-national-league-news |title=Zimmermann, Gorzelanny, Clippard agree with Nats |publisher=Newsok.com |date=January 17, 2012 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> Clippard became the de facto [[closer (baseball)|closer]] for the Nationals in the first half of the 2012 season. After injuries to Storen and [[Brad Lidge]], [[Henry Rodr<U+00ED>guez (pitcher)|Henry Rodriguez]] became the closer, but Rodriguez lost the job to Clippard due to his struggles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csnwashington.com/baseball-washington-nationals/nationals-talk/Clippard-stays-as-closer-Lidge-setting-u?blockID=721794&feedID=6358|title=Clippard stays as closer, Lidge setting up|last=Zuckerman|first=Mark|date=June 8, 2012|publisher=[[Comcast Sportsnet]]|accessdate=June 11, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Wagner |first=James |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/nationals-journal/post/thrust-into-new-roles-because-of-injuries-sean-burnett-tyler-clippard-are-excelling/2012/06/22/gJQA49tXvV_blog.html |title=Thrust into new roles because of injuries, Sean Burnett, Tyler Clippard are excelling|work=Nationals Journal |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=Jule 22, 2012|accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Kilgore |first=Adam |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/nationals-journal/post/nationals-move-henry-rodriguez-out-of-closers-role-and-tyler-clippard-wants-the-job/2012/05/22/gIQA6wSyiU_blog.html |title=Nationals move Henry Rodriguez out of closer<U+2019>s role, and Tyler Clippard wants the job|work=Nationals Journal |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=May 22, 2012 |accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref> The Nationals kept Clippard as their closer even after Storen returned to the team.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wagner |first=James |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/nationals-journal/post/tyler-clippard-to-remain-nationals-closer-even-when-drew-storen-returns-from-injury/2012/06/24/gJQAtAamyV_blog.html |title=Tyler Clippard to remain Nationals closer even when Drew Storen returns from injury|work=Nationals Journal |newspaper=The Washington Post|date=June 24, 2012 |accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref> He was named the [[Major League Baseball Delivery Man of the Month]] for his performance in June 2012, recording ten saves in ten opportunities, and allowing zero runs in {{frac|11|2|3}} innings pitched.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120702&content_id=34325478&vkey=pr_mlb&c_id=mlb |title=Tyler Clippard of the Washington Nationals named the Major League Baseball Delivery Man of the Month for June |work=MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball |date=July 2, 2012 |accessdate=July 4, 2012}}</ref>

==Scouting report==
Clippard is listed at {{convert|6|ft|4|in}} and {{convert|170|lbs}}.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kepner|first=Tyler|url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B03E4DB1E31F933A15756C0A9619C8B63|title=Baseball&nbsp;<U+2014> Farm-Fresh Products|newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 20, 2007|accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> He has an unorthodox pitching delivery,<ref name=pasco>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=KMsNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=fXQDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4945,932188&dq=tyler-clippard+mitchell&hl=en|title=Ex-Pasco star makes pitch for glory|first=Izzy|last=Gould|newspaper=St. Petersburg Times|page=1|date=May 22, 2007|accessdate=July 10, 2012}}</ref> rocking forward while sticking his gloved hand high in the air,<ref name=kepner>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/21/sports/baseball/21yankees.html?ref=baseball|title=Magical Night for Rookie Pitcher|first=Tyler|last=Kepner|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 21, 2007|accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> which creates an unusual arm angle while pitching, making it difficult for hitters to pick up the ball in their line of vision.<ref name=washingtontimes>{{cite web|author=2 Photos|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2011/jul/11/nats-clippard-set-up-to-succeed/|title=Nats' Clippard set up to succeed|publisher=Washington Times|date=2011-07-11|accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> Clippard's father taught him to pitch this way when Clippard was eight years old by having him throw his [[baseball glove]].<ref name=washingtontimes/> McCatty nicknamed Clippard's delivery "The Funk".<ref name=washingtontimes/>

Clippard primarily throws a [[fastball]] and a [[changeup]]. His hard, straight [[four-seam fastball]] averages about {{convert|93|mph}}, topping out at {{convert|96|mph}}, and sets up a deceptive changeup in the low 80s. Periodically, he throws a cutter early in the count to right-handed hitters and a curveball in the upper 70s.<ref>{{cite web|title=PITCHf/x Player Card: Tyler Clippard|url=http://brooksbaseball.net/player_cards/player_card.php?player=461325|publisher=BrooksBaseball.net|accessdate=April 27, 2012}}</ref> [[Nardi Contreras]], who worked with Clippard as the Yankees' minor league pitching coordinator, indicated that Clippard's greatest success comes from his curveball and changeup.<ref name=kepner/>

Clippard has compiled a [[K/9|strikeout rate]] of greater than 10 per 9 innings over his career. According to Clippard, "I don't try to strike out everyone that I face. Strikeouts just kind of happen with the way I pitch."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fangraphs.com/blogs/index.php/qa-nationals-closer-tyler-clippard/|title=Q&A: Nationals Closer Tyler Clippard|last=Laurila|first=David|date=June 15, 2012|work=[[Fangraphs]]|accessdate=3 August 2012}}</ref>

{{As of|2012|9|4|df=US}}, Clippard has the lowest [[ground ball/fly ball ratio]] among active pitchers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=pit&lg=all&qual=y&type=2&season=2012&month=0&season1=1871&ind=0&team=0&rost=1&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=3,a|title=Major League Leaderboards <U+00BB> 2012 <U+00BB> Pitchers <U+00BB> Batted Ball Statistics|work=[[Fangraphs]]|accessdate=5 September 2012}}</ref> Compared to other right-handed pitchers, Clippard is much more likely to throw pitches high in the [[strike zone]] or above it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseballprospectus.com/pitchfx/pitcher_profiles/pitcher_profiles.php?player=461325&month=&year=&throws=&pi_type=&report=count&color=&normType=R|title=PitchFX Pitcher Profile: Tyler Clippard|work=Baseball Prospectus|accessdate=5 September 2012}}</ref>

==Personal==
Clippard was raised by his father, Bob, and his mother, Debbie.<ref name=tampabay/> He has a brother, named Colin, who played Little League baseball with Tyler.<ref name=tampabay/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/tampabay/access/21183711.html?dids=21183711:21183711&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jul+12%252C+1995&author=WAYNE+McKNIGHT&pub=St.+Petersburg+Times&desc=Battaglia%252C+Butler+team+to+lead+Countryside+Series%253A+Pinellas+SPORTS+EXTRA&pqatl=google |title=Battaglia, Butler team to lead Countryside Series: Pinellas Sports Extra|newspaper=St. Petersburg Times |first=Wayne|last=McKnight|page=5.C|date=July 12, 1995 |accessdate=July 6, 2012}} {{subscription required|date=July 2012}}</ref>

